# Project Folder Structure Guidelines

This document provides a high-level overview, directory layouts, and design conventions for both **Single-Role** and **Multi-Role** application setups. Please refer to this guide to maintain architectural consistency across the engineering team.

---

## 1. Shared Project Directory Layout

Both single-role and multi-role setups share the exact same root directory layout. The only difference is the internal structure of the `app/` folder.

```
project_root/
├── .expo/                 # Expo build metadata and temporary configurations
├── .vscode/               # VS Code workspace settings
├── android/               # Native Android build folder
├── app/                   # Expo Router routing directory (pages/screens) - [Detailed below]
├── assets/                # App static media files
│   ├── graphic/           # Graphic designs and illustration elements
│   ├── icons/             # Custom application icons
│   └── images/            # Standard PNG/JPEG images
├── components/            # Reusable UI components
│   ├── global/            # Application-wide global elements (cards, modals)
│   ├── layout/            # Layout structure components (header, footer, drawer)
│   ├── module/            # Feature-specific subcomponents (auth, dashboard)
│   └── ui/                # Core UI primitives (buttons, inputs, status indicators)
├── constants/             # App-wide constants
├── context/               # React Context providers (redirections, themes)
├── docs/               # React Context providers (redirections, themes)
├── hooks/                 # Reusable React custom hooks
├── lib/                   # Third-party integrations & utilities (Stripe, Axios)
├── services/              # API network requests definitions
└── types/                 # TypeScript type declarations
```

---

## 2. Structure inside the `app/` Folder

Depending on the role architecture, structure the `app/` directory according to one of the options below:

### Option A: Single-Role Setup (Flat Routing)

For applications catering to only one primary actor (e.g., a customer). Authentication, onboarding, and tabs are mounted directly under `app/`:

```
app/
├── (auth)/            # Authentication flow routes (sign-in, sign-up, etc.)
├── (onboarding)/      # App onboarding flow screens
├── (tabs)/            # Main tab layout navigation (e.g., Home, Profile)
│   ├── tab-1/         # First tab sub-pages and main screen
│   ├── tab-2/         # Second tab sub-pages and main screen
│   ├── tab-3/         # Third tab sub-pages and main screen
│   └── tab-4/         # Fourth tab sub-pages and main screen
└── (routes)/          # Non-tab sub-pages (e.g., detail views, setting overrides)
```

### Option B: Multi-Role Setup (Role-Based Routing)

For applications managing multiple distinct roles in the same codebase. Routes and screens are segregated under specific role folders:

```
app/
├── (auth)/            # Authentication flow routes
├── (role_1)/          # Workspace for role type 1 (e.g., Cleaner)
│   ├── (routes)/      # Sub-pages for cleaners
│   └── (tabs)/        # Tab navigation for cleaners
├── (role_2)/          # Workspace for role type 2 (e.g., Maintenance)
│   ├── (routes)/      # Sub-pages for maintenance
│   └── (tabs)/        # Tab navigation for maintenance
└── (role_3)/          # Workspace for role type 3 (e.g., Admin)
    ├── (routes)/      # Sub-pages for admin tasks
    └── (tabs)/        # Tab navigation for admin tasks
```

